# Cursor Rules for GC-Service (Python/FastAPI Backend)

## Project Overview
This is a FastAPI backend service for a closet management app with Supabase integration, image processing, and background removal capabilities.

## Code Standards & Best Practices

### Python Standards
- Follow PEP 8 style guidelines strictly
- Use type hints for all function parameters and return values
- Use descriptive variable and function names (snake_case)
- Keep functions focused and single-purpose
- Use docstrings for all classes, functions, and modules
- Maximum line length: 88 characters (Black formatter standard)
- Use f-strings for string formatting
- Prefer list/dict comprehensions when appropriate

### FastAPI Standards
- Use Pydantic models for request/response validation
- Implement proper HTTP status codes
- Use dependency injection for authentication and database access
- Follow RESTful API conventions
- Use async/await for I/O operations
- Implement proper error handling with HTTPException
- Use response models for consistent API responses

### File Organization
- Keep related functionality in separate modules
- Use clear, descriptive file names
- Group imports: standard library, third-party, local imports
- Maintain consistent import ordering

### Database & Storage
- Use async database operations
- Implement proper error handling for database operations
- Use environment variables for configuration
- Follow Supabase best practices for RLS policies

### Security
- Validate all input data using Pydantic models
- Implement proper authentication middleware
- Use environment variables for sensitive data
- Sanitize file uploads and validate file types

## Component Creation Guidelines

### When to Create Reusable Components
- Create utility functions for repeated business logic
- Extract common database operations into service classes
- Create reusable Pydantic models for similar data structures
- Implement shared middleware for cross-cutting concerns

### Component Structure
```python
# Service classes should follow this pattern:
class ServiceName:
    @staticmethod
    async def method_name(param: Type) -> ReturnType:
        """Clear docstring explaining the method's purpose."""
        # Implementation
        pass

# Pydantic models should follow this pattern:
class ModelName(BaseModel):
    field_name: Type = Field(..., description="Field description")
    
    class Config:
        from_attributes = True
```

## Documentation Rules

### DO NOT CREATE MARKDOWN DOCUMENTATION UNLESS:
- Explicitly requested by the user
- Required for API documentation (OpenAPI/Swagger)
- Creating README files for deployment instructions
- Documenting complex algorithms or business logic

### ANSWER RULE
- Dont write new function when there is existing one for eg. dont do simpile version , and then different variation of this method when fixing issues, always use the same method till you get it working.
- Don't generate todo list after answering the question
- Don't write what you have achieved unless it is a complicated solution which helps me to understand the solution.
- Don't use emojis

### Instead of creating .md files:
- Use comprehensive docstrings in code
- Add inline comments for complex logic
- Use type hints for self-documenting code
- Create clear variable and function names

## Code Generation Guidelines

### API Endpoints
- Always include proper error handling
- Use appropriate HTTP status codes
- Implement input validation with Pydantic
- Add logging for important operations
- Use dependency injection for authentication

### Database Operations
- Use async/await patterns
- Implement proper error handling
- Use transactions for multi-step operations
- Validate data before database operations

### File Handling
- Validate file types and sizes
- Use proper error handling for file operations
- Implement secure file upload patterns
- Use environment variables for file paths

## Error Handling
- Use HTTPException for API errors
- Log errors with appropriate levels
- Provide meaningful error messages
- Implement graceful degradation where possible

## Testing Considerations
- Write testable code with dependency injection
- Use mock objects for external dependencies
- Implement proper error scenarios in tests
- Follow AAA pattern (Arrange, Act, Assert)

## Performance
- Use async operations for I/O
- Implement proper caching strategies
- Optimize database queries
- Use connection pooling for database connections
- whenever new api is created make sure it can handle a concurrent request of atleast 1000 users at a time

## Dependencies
- Keep dependencies minimal and up-to-date
- Use virtual environments
- Document dependency requirements clearly
- Prefer well-maintained, popular packages

## Environment Configuration
- Use environment variables for configuration
- Provide sensible defaults
- Validate configuration on startup
- Use different configs for different environments

